english:
  title: Two Verses on Idle Leisure
  author: Kang Hi-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Long leisure comes not from many skills possessed,
    Yet what becomes of lofty aims as age draws near?
    Twenty years of seeking rank have only brought
    White frost upon my temples; dawn wind scatters lamp flames.

    Once I followed office-seekers to the palace gate,
    Gladly taking my place with gulls upon the blue waters.
    Now in my declining years I've chosen my resting place—
    The river at Yanghwajin shines like a mirror freshly ground.

    Many moons and years have passed in wandering far,
    I ask now: what word comes of old friends?
    In the short fence, withered chrysanthemums lack their beauty in the cold,
    Frost gathers thick on tiles, yet still its flowers dazzle.

    Mountains embrace my old home, wreathed in deepest green,
    The moon peers through the pass and stirs its waves of gold.
    The knots that bind us human hearts—these cannot be untied.
    So now my dull blade needs no further grinding.
  footnotes:
    - Yanghwajin refers to the Yanghwajin area near Seoul, known for its scenic riverside views and historical significance during the Joseon period.
    - The imagery of 'dull blade' and 'grinding' is a metaphor for efforts at self-improvement and advancement in the world—suggesting the speaker has abandoned such ambitions.
